node.title: Flood threat eases in Gippsland but more wild weather coming in Victoria
node.description: Floodwaters in the Mitchell and Avon rivers in Gippsland are receding but the weather bureau has issued a severe weather warning for damaging winds for parts of the state.
node.content: ["More wild weather is predicted for Victoria today but the threat of flooding in Gippsland has eased.", "The Victorian State Emergency Service responded to more than 240 calls for assistance in the 24 hours to 6am on Sunday, including 15 rescues.", "Five people were left hanging on to trees after their car was trapped by floodwaters under the Wuk Wuk Bridge near Bairnsdale, in East Gippsland.", "Major flood warnings remain in place for the Mitchell and Avon rivers but floodwaters have peaked overnight and are now receding.", "The Bureau of Meteorology (BOM) said the Avon River peaked above 6.54 metres at Stratford on Saturday night, but had\u00a0been steadily falling below the major flood level.", "There was major flooding reported at Stratford.", "Moderate flooding was reported at Glenaladale, where the Mitchell River peaked at 4.71 metres on Saturday.", "The BOM's Keris Arndt said the major flood warning would\u00a0remain in place for the Mitchell and Avon rivers in the short term.", "\"There's definitely still elevated flooding through these rivers, still danger around fast-flowing waters, so just be well aware that there is a still a lot of water around even though they may have peaked and dropped below major flood levels,\" he said.", "The SES said there was minimal risk to property from the flooding, but some homes might\u00a0be isolated due to road closures.", "The weather bureau issued a severe weather warning for damaging winds for parts of the Central, East Gippsland, South West, North East, and West\u00a0and South Gippsland districts today.", "\"We do have a cold front moving through the state this morning, bringing showers and potentially some isolated thunderstorms and small hail to much of the state, especially in southern parts and quite gusty winds as well,\" Mr Arndt said.", "The bureau said the strong and gusty winds would most affect the exposed coasts and Alpine districts, where wind gusts were expected to reach 100 kilometres per hour."]
